Pine needles are a form of forest-bio-residue having all the characteristics of being seen as an important source of renewable energy [4], especially in the western region of the Himalayas in India (refer to Fig. 1
                     , Fig. 2
                     ). It must be addressed as a resource because it is highly inflammable and a destructive source of engulfing fires and carbon emissions apart from the huge damage it causes every year [5] (refer to Fig. 3
                     ). As per Uttarakhand Forest Department data [6], pine trees range across half a million hectares of the forest area in the state. In 2019, forest fires due to pine residue affected 1244.64 ha of forest. It adds nearly 500 million kilograms of CO2 every year into Uttarakhand's atmosphere [7].
